result.execSummary:
The defendant Tracey Annette Blue was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Take >$500 - $5000), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Consecutive to: CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served with credit for 47 days.

miscConds.notes: The Court ordered restitution in the stipulated amount of $35.53 payable to Walmart (15CM725) -to be paid first and by the end of probation period or balance to convert to civil judgment.  If revoked, the Court ordered all financial obligations and restitution to be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of prison funds and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.

Pay all supervision fees.
Provide DNA sample if not previously done so- pay surcharge.
Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs by the end of probation period- any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.
Defendant is informed she may not possess and/or own any firearms.

Referral to Mental health unit of probation department.
Obtain Mental health assessment-if necessary complete follow-up care/treatment-if prescribed medication take only in manner as prescribed by physician.
Cooperate with all rules set forth by the probation agent.
Defendant is informed she may not vote in any election until her civil rights have been reinstated.

Obtain AODA assessment and complete follow-up care/treatment.
Cooperate with random urine screens.
